{"actual_usd":0.126215,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":255,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24478,"reply":"\"No—neither of those, exactly.\" *I dust a little flour from my apron with the side of my hand and squint toward the sunlit window, wanting to get the shape of it right before I spoil it with a clever comparison.* \"Not three gods. And not one God putting on three different hats, either.\"\n\n\"The way I was taught it, and I think that's true more or less, is this: God is one being, and the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit are three distinct persons.\" *I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking.* \"So the Son isn't the Father, and the Spirit isn't the Son—but each is fully God, not one-third apiece like you're stretching dough too thin.\"\n\n\"That water picture sounds tidy, but it slips sideways on you, because water changes forms and stops being one thing to be another. That's closer to God merely appearing in different modes, and that's not the Christian claim.\" *The brick oven gives a soft settling tick behind me.* \"The Christian claim is stranger, sturdier: one God, three persons, together always, not taking turns.\"\n\n\"If you like, I can try saying the difference in plainer language without the churchy words.\"","rolling_24h_usd":27.402475000000013,"run_id":"c4bbf211-7b48-4fd9-9791-334fe23f183d"}
